metadata.name: September #182
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle “live mode”. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)

metadata.name: Returns #461
metadata.description:
Returns is an offline-first PWA and an interactive SVG. It combines the joy of interaction, digital color and minimalist sculpture with the potential of a long running, continuously unique visual. Based on “Shipping” from 2016, it is inspired by Anne Truitt, Ugo Rondinone, Imi Knoebel, Kelly Ellsworth and many others.

A subdivision slices the viewport influenced by width, height and depth. Corners are cut by replacing them with two new points, pulled towards each other along the edges. Shapes are “rounded" by repeating this step, keeping the new points close together. As colors change, so do the relations between shapes, even if geometry changes at a slower pace. New compositions are created on click or after a timeout. This progress over time allows for infinite iterations within the space of each token. It is the promise of a seeded starting point, plus the potential for unlimited new and unique iterations and states over time.

metadata.name: 03. world of boxland #61
metadata.description:
Boxland is made of boxes, of 262.144 boxes to be more precise. These boxes are rearranged whenever an observer moves around generating an infinite landscape.

Landscape is generated using fbm noise at different frequencies so the algorithm can define areas where there is water, shores that are in constant movement and the mountains that can get high up to the sky. 

Users can control the camera point of view, although it is always performing a fly through the never ending world.


Features tied to the hash : 
- General color palette
- Landscape seed
- Water amount (you can get archipelagos or vast landscapes)
- Camera position

metadata.name: Offset Disorder #43
metadata.description:
This work is an experiment using generated risograph halftones and hand-drawn elements to create a highly textured pattern. 

- Viewing in Chrome is recommended.
- Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. 
- Image size is 1200x1200px.

Common Features:
- Random 3 to 10 color palette using colors from p5riso
- Individual color layer shifts from 2 to 20px
- Simplex or square color noise patters
- Glitches resulting in hand-drawn shapes
- Glitch rate of 10-50% of shapes

Less Common
- Linear color distribution (top -> bottom)
- Up to 5 large hand-drawn circles
- Very high glitch rate of 50%

Rare
- Perfect color alignment with no errors

metadata.name: David #6
metadata.description:
Oh David!

Need I introduce him?

The Biblical hero. The symbol of strength and youthful beauty. The size.

He was supposedly gazing at the direction of the Medici family. We gaze at him.

We measure him with laser scanners in the Digital Michelangelo Project. And as Guan Xiao sang in her David (2013) at Biennale di Venezia (2017), we study him, shoot him, sing for him, sculpture him, draw him, reproduce him.

His eyes. His gaze. His view point.

Does it give me power if I arrange him, rotate him, and color him?

Does it give me power to go inside his head and look outwards?

metadata.name: let me fall #173
metadata.description:
A study of form, empty spaces, panic attacks, asymmetry, tinnitus, chaos, and the never-ending journey to obtain imperfection. 

30 Matisse-inspired palettes.

2-6 – increase resolution.

“f” – add more noise to iteration at current resolution.
“n” – redraw at current resolution without noise.
“s” – save export.

Please be patient while drawing at higher resolutions, it can take quite a while.

Created with p5js.

metadata.name: Triangles #16
metadata.description:
Slowly-forming triangles change over time.

Features:

- Palettes are chosen from a curated range. The most common size has six colours, but there is a chance of three, seven or eight.

- Triangle orientation takes two forms. These are subtly blended over time.

- Spacing and grid size are chosen from weighted values.

This piece is designed for display and changes slowly over time. Resizing the window will produce the same pattern, but progress so far will be cleared and the formation process will start again. This is because the pattern is produced by layering over time.

If you are new to coding or otherwise interested in learning, please feel free to browse the code. Effort has been made to explain, as best as possible, how everything works with comments.
